The fluorescence spectra of AN-CDs exhibited a significant response to epinephrine, with the intense blue fluorescence peak being quenched by 90 % upon its addition, while the fluorescence was not significantly enhanced or quenched by other biomarkers. This demonstrates the ability of the AN-CDs probe to sense epinephrine. Additionally, increasing concentrations of epinephrine resulted in inversely proportional quenching in emission intensity at 430 nm (Fig. 5
                        a). Various concentrations of epinephrine were used to measure the emission intensity of AN-CDs (Fig. 5b). The results showed that the fluorescence intensity ratio (I0/I) at 430 nm was amplified by higher concentrations of epinephrine (Fig. 5c). A calibration graph was created by plotting the emission intensity ratio (I0/I) against epinephrine concentrations ranging from 0.05 to 50 µM. The graph demonstrated excellent linearity, showing a correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) of 0.9869. In this context, I0 corresponds to the emission intensity measured without epinephrine, while I correspond to the emission intensity observed when epinephrine is present (Fig. 5b). The LOD for AN-CDs was determined to be 37.04 nM, indicating their high sensitivity. When compared with alternative analytical methods, the fluorescence method using AN-CDs achieved a lower LOD (Table 1
                        ) [43,44,46,47].
